fields.name: Species
fields.description: As it stands, there are 393 prospective neighbors in Animal Crossing that are made up of 35 different animal species.

fields.name: Personality
fields.description: There are eight different personalities in Animal Crossing: Normal, Lazy, Sisterly, Snooty, Cranky, Jock, Peppy, and Smug.

fields.name: Popular
fields.description: Most popular villagers in Animal Crossing.

fields.name: Alligator
fields.description: There are nine alligator villagers so far. There are currently no peppy, smug, or sisterly alligators. Of the alligators, two are normal, one is snooty, three are lazy, two are jock, and one is cranky.

fields.name: Cats
fields.description: There are thirty cats in the series. Four cats are special characters and the remaining twenty-six are villagers, of which five are snooty, five are lazy, six are peppy, two are cranky, three are jock, and three are normal. There is only one sisterly and smug cat, Katt and Raymond respectively. Cats are the most prevalent species of villagers.

fields.name: Wolf
fields.description: There are thirteen wolf villagers, of which five are cranky, three are snooty, two are smug, one is normal, one is jock, and one is peppy.

fields.name: Duck
fields.description: There are a total of nineteen duck villagers, of which four are jock, four are lazy, four are snooty, four are peppy, two are normal, and one is smug. There are no cranky or sisterly ducks.

fields.name: Octopus
fields.description: There are only four octopus villagers, making them the rarest villager type. There is one jock octopus, one normal octopus, one cranky octopus, and one lazy octopus. There are no peppy, snooty, sisterly, or smug octopuses.

fields.name: Elephant
fields.description: There is a total of thirteen elephant villagers, of which one is jock, four are lazy, one is peppy, three are normal, three are snooty and one is cranky. There are no sisterly or smug elephants.

fields.name: Rabbit
fields.description: There are twenty-one rabbit villagers, of which eight are peppy, four are lazy, two are snooty, two are jock, two are smug, one is cranky, one is normal, and one is sisterly.

fields.name: Normal
fields.description: Normal villagers, despite being called "normal", have a lack of self-worth, where they feel self-depreciative. They also appear slightly obsessive with cleanliness and hygiene - a trait also found in peppy villagers.

fields.name: Peppy
fields.description: They are incessantly friendly and excitable, making them very quick to apologize for anything they regret doing, even if they had not done anything particularly wrong.

fields.name: Snooty
fields.description: They are called snooty villagers because they act more mature and higher-class than other villagers. They are usually portrayed wearing makeup and high-end clothes that match their style, and their homes appear luxurious, though there are some exceptions.

fields.name: Cranky
fields.description: Cranky villagers (also called Grumpy villagers), are male villagers in the Animal Crossing series. The name is a direct reference to the meaning of cranky; someone who is irritated or annoyed easily. As of now, there are 63 cranky villagers.

fields.name: Lazy
fields.description: Lazy villagers have a relaxed, easygoing, and little kiddish approach to living in the town. They are generally friendly and hospitable when interacting with the player and other villagers, and they are fairly confident in themselves and their lifestyle.

fields.name: Smug
fields.description: Smug villagers are very polite, kind, and gentleman-like, and will easily get along with other villagers. They seem to be a mix between all personality types and are lively, kind, and positive, but may come off as conceited.

fields.name: Jock
fields.description: A jock is a personality type defined by their key interests in physical fitness and sports, including wrestling and typical gym exercises such as leg-squats and push-ups.

fields.name: Squirrel
fields.description: Squirrels are a species of villager in the Animal Crossing series. They are most noted for their fluffy, curled tails. There are twenty-four squirrel villagers. Of these twenty-four squirrels, four are peppy, four are snooty, nine are normal, one is lazy, one is sisterly, two are jock, one is smug, and two are cranky.

fields.name: Sisterly
fields.description: Sisterly villagers will, when befriended, give the player fighting tips and teach them ways to relax. These villagers are tough but they still care deeply about their appearance. They have a tendency to stay up very late into the night.

fields.name: Dogs
fields.description: There is a total of twenty-seven dogs in total in the Animal Crossing series. Eight of these are special characters and the remaining nineteen are villagers, of which three are peppy, one is snooty, three are normal, one is sisterly, seven are lazy, two are jock, two are cranky, and one is smug.

fields.name: Koala
fields.description: There are eleven koala villagers with four being normal, one being sisterly, one being smug, one being cranky, one being peppy, one being jock, one being lazy, and one being snooty. Yuka is the only koala to have appeared in every game to date.

fields.name: Horse
fields.description: Horses are a species of villager in the Animal Crossing series. There are seventeen horses, of which two are snooty, one is jock, three are lazy, three are smug, three are peppy, three are normal, one is cranky and one is sisterly.

fields.name: Ruby
fields.description: Ruby is a peppy rabbit villager from the Animal Crossing series. Her name refers to the gem ruby, since her eyes are a deep red, which is an effect of albinism — a condition which, in the real world, is more common in rabbits than any other animal due to selective breeding.

fields.name: Tia
fields.description: Tia is a normal elephant villager in the Animal Crossing series. Tia seems to be based on a teapot.

fields.name: Coco
fields.description: Coco is a normal rabbit villager from the Animal Crossing series. Her English name probably comes from the coconut, a fruit stereotypically depicted with three holes.

fields.name: Pompom
fields.description: Pompom is a peppy duck villager who has appeared in every Animal Crossing series game to date. Her name does not relate to her species, but her initial phrase, "rah rah", relates to cheerleading, and because peppy villagers aspire to become cheerleaders.

fields.name: Zucker
fields.description: Zucker is a lazy octopus villager who first appeared in New Leaf. His Japanese name and general appearance refers to the Japanese snack takoyaki (たこ焼き), which is a fried ball of dough commonly filled with minced octopus. His catchphrase is a reference to how he is an underwater animal.

fields.name: Wolfgang
fields.description: Wolfgang is a cranky wolf villager who has appeared in every game in the Animal Crossing series so far. His name is derived from the same name in the German language. His picture quote in. Wild World.

fields.name: Cole
fields.description: Cole is a lazy rabbit villager who first appeared in Animal Crossing: New Leaf. His name is likely a play on "coal", relating to his black color. His Japanese name comes from the Amami rabbit.

fields.name: Eloise
fields.description: Eloise is a snooty elephant villager in the Animal Crossing series. Her name is derived from the word elephant, which is her species, similar to Ellie, a normal elephant. Her initial catchphrase, "tooooot," is a reference to the sound elephants with their trunks.

fields.name: Rudy
fields.description: Rudy is a jock, cat villager in the Animal Crossing series. He first appeared in Animal Crossing: New Leaf. His English name may be a reference to Rudolph, a famous reindeer, who has a red nose like Rudy. ... His picture quote is a reference to the popular phrase "cats always land on their feet."

fields.name: Filbert
fields.description: As a lazy villager, Filbert will be friendly and easy to get along with due to his laid back lifestyle. Like all lazy villagers, he has a love of food and relaxing. He will enjoy partaking in the usual hobbies, usually for relaxing reasons or for food, like when fishing. Filbert will get along well with other villagers, but may offend or confuse jock villagers, who have a lifestyle of exercise and fitness, which conflicts with the lazy lifestyle of relaxing and food.

fields.name: Hazel
fields.description: Hazel is a sisterly villager. When befriended, she will give the player fighting tips and teach them ways to relax. Hazel will also give the player medicine if they are stung by a bee. Like all sisterly villagers, Hazel is tough, but she will still care deeply about her appearance. Hazel has a tendency to stay up very late at night. It is easy to get her picture since developing friendships with sisterly villagers is simple due to her caring and protective nature.

fields.name: Poppy
fields.description: Poppy is a dusky red squirrel with a cream muzzle, tail stripe, and tipped paws. Poppy has a normal personality, and frequently acts kind towards the player. Normal villagers generally get along well with lazy, peppy, smug, snooty and other normal villagers. Poppy may conflict with cranky and sisterly villagers. As a normal villager, Poppy will usually wake up at 6:00 am and is easier to befriend than most.

fields.name: Biskit
fields.description: Biskit is a lazy dog villager in the Animal Crossing series, appearing in every game to date. As a lazy villager, Biskit will be friendly and easy to get along with due to his laid back lifestyle. Like all lazy villagers, he has a love of food and relaxing. He will enjoy partaking in the usual hobbies, usually for relaxing reasons or for food, like when fishing.

fields.name: Chrissy
fields.description: Chrissy is a peppy rabbit villager in the Animal Crossing series. Peppy villagers appear to be in a good mood often and are easy to become friends with. As a peppy villager, Chrissy will have the tendency to over-react in conversations about trivial subjects, and will usually be over-excited to see the player or other villagers.

fields.name: Bunnie
fields.description: Bunnie is a peppy rabbit villager from the Animal Crossing series. Peppy villagers appear to be in a good mood often and are easy to become friends with. As a peppy villager, Bunnie will have the tendency to over-react in conversations about trivial subjects, and will usually be over-excited to see the player or other villagers.

fields.name: Sly
fields.description: Sly is a jock alligator villager in New Leaf. His Japanese name comes from his appearance, which is camouflage. Sly has a jock personality and has a great interest in sports and bodybuilding. Jock villagers are hyperactive and motivated but often come across as egotistical and dense. As a jock villager, Sly is very interested in his hobby, and may compete against the player at catching bugs and fish.

fields.name: Carmen
fields.description: Carmen is a peppy rabbit villager who was introduced in Animal Crossing: City Folk. In New Horizons, Carmen has the fashion hobby and will be more frequently seen visiting Able Sisters and commenting on the player's fashion, sometimes giving them clothes that match their current outfit in color or style. She may be found carrying around a purse or wearing accessories and clothing different from their initial or gifted outfits.

fields.name: Mitzi
fields.description: Mitzi is a normal cat villager who has appeared in all the games in the Animal Crossing series. Mitzi is a kind and calm character like all normal villagers. She will easily become upset or offended by other villagers, particularly lazy villagers who mislead her and cranky villagers who have a rude nature. She enjoys the usual hobbies, such as fishing and bug catching, usually to keep her active.

fields.name: Drago
fields.description: Drago is a lazy alligator villager who first appears in Animal Crossing: New Leaf. As a lazy villager, Drago will enjoy napping and talking about food, as well as appearing calm and relaxed through most circumstances. Like other lazy villagers, he will share the same interests such as clothes, fishing, bug catching, and fossil hunting. When he talks about clothes, he may mention his alter-ego, "Fashion Lad," a hero made up by lazy villagers who tackles fashion disasters.

fields.name: Francine
fields.description:
Francine is a snooty, rabbit villager in the Animal Crossing series. She is the older sister of Chrissy.
In New Horizons, Francine has the fashion hobby and will be more frequently seen visiting Able Sisters and commenting on the player's fashion, sometimes giving them clothes that match their current outfit in color or style. She may be found carrying around a purse or wearing accessories and clothing different from their initial or gifted outfits.

fields.name: Marina
fields.description: Marina is a normal, octopus villager whose debut appearance was in Doubutsu no Mori e+ as an islander. She later re-appeared in Animal Crossing: Wild World, Animal Crossing: City Folk, and Animal Crossing: New Leaf where she is a villager. In New Horizons, Marina has the music hobby and will be more frequently seen singing or dancing. If a stereo is set outside with a song playing, she will sing to the melody; if other instruments are set up, such as drums or guitars, she may play along.

fields.name: Ozzie
fields.description: Ozzie is a lazy koala villager from the Animal Crossing series. His name is derived from the term "Aussie", which is another word for "Australian." His Japanese name means "acorn," referring to his nose. In New Horizons, Ozzie has the play hobby and will be more frequently seen running around the island, sometimes with other villagers. He may also set up treasure hunts (a timed minigame) with the player. Ozzie, as a lazy villager, will be easy to get along with due to his laid back lifestyle.

fields.name: Winnie
fields.description: Winnie is a peppy, horse villager from the Animal Crossing series. She was absent from Animal Crossing: Wild World and returns in Animal Crossing: City Folk. In New Horizons, Winnie has the fashion hobby and will be more frequently seen visiting Able Sisters and commenting on the player's fashion, sometimes giving them clothes that match their current outfit in color or style. She may be found carrying around a purse or wearing accessories and clothing different from their initial or gifted outfits.

fields.name: Skye
fields.description: Skye is a normal wolf villager who first appeared in Animal Crossing: New Leaf. Her name is derived from her appearance, which resembles the sky and clouds. In New Horizons, Skye has the music hobby and will be more frequently seen singing or dancing. If a stereo is set outside with a song playing, she will sing to the melody; if other instruments are set up, such as drums or guitars, she may play along. Skye has a normal personality, so she will be a pleasant villager.

fields.name: Clyde
fields.description: Clyde is a lazy horse villager who first appears in Animal Crossing: City Folk. His English and Japanese names may both be derived from Clydesdale, a horse breed. In New Horizons, Clyde has the play hobby and will be more frequently seen running around the island, sometimes with other villagers. He may also set up treasure hunts (a timed minigame) with the player. Clyde is a lazy villager who likes food, often bringing up the subject of random foods in regular conversation.

fields.name: Peaches
fields.description: Peaches is a normal horse villager in the Animal Crossing series, appearing in every game except for Animal Crossing: Wild World and Animal Crossing: Pocket Camp. Her catchphrase, "neighbor," is a pun on the sound horses make. In New Horizons, Peaches has the education hobby and will be more frequently seen reading books and visiting the museum. Peaches has a normal personality. She is shy and caring, and may get upset easily.

fields.name: Kiki
fields.description: Kiki is a normal cat villager who has appeared in every Animal Crossing series game. In New Horizons, Kiki has the education hobby and will be more frequently seen reading books and visiting the museum. Kiki has a normal personality. She is shy and caring, and may get upset easily and may tell the player to stay away from her, but she does not take it out on them. She wakes up at 5:00 a.m. like other normal villagers, and may appear inside towards the middle of the day.

fields.name: Lolly
fields.description: Lolly is a cat villager with a normal personality in the Animal Crossing series, who first appeared in Doubutsu no Mori e+. Like most normal or "sweet" villagers, Lolly will be very sensitive and kind. She will be easily upset or offended by other villagers, particularly lazy or cranky villagers. She enjoys the usual hobbies, which are fashion, bug catching, fishing, and furniture. She will get along well with other normal villagers and peppy villagers, appearing mother-like in conversation.

fields.name: Punchy
fields.description: Punchy is a cat villager in the Animal Crossing series with a lazy personality. In New Horizons, Punchy has the play hobby and will be more frequently seen running around the island, sometimes with other villagers. He may also set up treasure hunts (a timed minigame) with the player. As a lazy villager, Punchy will be easy to get along with due to his laid back lifestyle. Like all lazy villagers, he shares a love of food and relaxing.

fields.name: Fang
fields.description: Fang is a cranky, wolf villager in the Animal Crossing series. He did not appear in Animal Crossing: Wild World, but reappeared in Animal Crossing: City Folk. In New Horizons, Fang has the education hobby and will be more frequently seen reading books and visiting the museum. Fang has a cranky personality, meaning that he can be quite rude to the player and be all around grumpy. He will warm up to the player as time goes on, and may eventually become a close friend.

fields.name: Cookie
fields.description: Cookie is a peppy dog villager in the Animal Crossing series. She is absent from Animal Crossing: Wild World, but returns in Animal Crossing: City Folk. In New Horizons, Cookie has the fashion hobby and will be more frequently seen visiting Able Sisters and commenting on the player's fashion, sometimes giving them clothes that match their current outfit in color or style. She may be found carrying around a purse or wearing accessories and clothing different from their initial or gifted outfits.

fields.name: Goldie
fields.description: Goldie is a normal dog villager, appearing in every game in the Animal Crossing series to date. Her name is based on the breed of dog she is, a Golden Retriever. In New Horizons, Goldie has the nature hobby and will be more frequently seen sitting underneath trees or observing and watering flowers. She will also fish and chase after bugs, and may also be seen carrying bundles of sticks or picnic baskets. Goldie has a normal personality, meaning that she is friendly and motherly towards the player, asking what she can do to help them often.
